{{Infobox National Olympic Committee | title = Olympic Committee of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea | logo = Olympic Committee of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.jpg | country = North Korea | code = PRK | created = 1953 | recognized = 1957 | president = Kim Il-guk | headquarters = P.O. Box 56 Kumsong-dong 2 Kwangbok Street [[Mangyongdae District]], [[Pyongyang]]<ref>https://www.olympic.org/democratic-people-s-republic-of-korea/</ref> }}
The '''Olympic Committee of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea''' ({{lang-ko|조선민주주의인민공화국 올림픽 위원회}}; [[List of IOC country codes|IOC code]]: '''PRK''') is the [[National Olympic Committee]] (NOC) representing [[North Korea]] (competing either as '''DPR Korea''' or as the country's full official name, the '''Democratic People's Republic of Korea''').<ref name="GrassoMallon2015"/>
It is a member of the [[Olympic Council of Asia]] (OCA),<ref name="ocas_Olym">{{Cite web | title = Olympic Council of Asia : National Olympic Committees | author = | work = ocasia.org | date = | accessdate = 2016-08-05 | url = http://www.ocasia.org/NOCS/NocsContact.aspx?iExK6qsiU4p+VnxSzEnnYQ== }}</ref> and of the [[Association of National Olympic Committees]] (ANOC).<ref name="acno_Kore">{{Cite web | title = Korea, Democratic People's Republic Of | work = acnolympic.org | date = | accessdate = 2016-08-05 | url = http://www.acnolympic.org/nocs/nocs-directory/asia/korea,-democratic-peoples-republic-of/ | language = | quote = }}</ref> It is based in [[Kwangbok Street]], [[Kumsong-dong]], [[Mangyongdae District]], [[Pyongyang]].<ref name="olym_Demo">{{Cite web | title = Democratic People's Republic of Korea - National Olympic Committee (NOC) | author = | work = International Olympic Committee | date = | accessdate = 2016-08-05 | url = https://www.olympic.org/democratic-people-s-republic-of-korea | quote = }}</ref> Its chairman is [[Kim Il-guk]],<ref name="naen_TheP">{{Cite web | title = National Olympic chairman chosen | agency = KCNA | work = The Pyongyang Times | date = 2017-01-24 | accessdate = 2017-05-16 | url = http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/order/pytimes/?page=Sports&no=23572 }}</ref> Vice President [[Chang Ung]], and Secretary General [[Son Kwang-ho]].<ref name="insi_RiJo">{{Cite web | title = Ri Jong Mu appointed new President of North Korean Olympic Committee | author = Nick Butler | work = insidethegames.biz | date = 20 March 2016 | accessdate = 2016-08-08 | url = http://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1035574/ri-jong-mu-appointed-new-president-of-north-korean-olympic-committee | language = | quote = }}</ref>
==History== Before the [[Korean War]], the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) recognized a single Korean [[National Olympic Committee]] (NOC) representing both the North and [[South Korea]], based in [[Seoul]]. After the war, North Korea displayed dissatisfaction with this arrangement, and repeatedly called for the creation of a North Korean NOC. The IOC declined these pleas on the grounds that there could be only one NOC per country.<ref name="Hill1996">{{cite book|last=Hill|first=Christopher R.|title=Olympic Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IPToAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA164|year=1996|publisher=Manchester University Press|location=Manchester|isbn=978-0-7190-4451-9|page=164}}</ref>
Regardless of the lack of recognition, the Olympic Committee of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea was founded in 1953<ref name="Hoare2012">{{cite book|author=James Hoare|title=Historical Dictionary of Democratic People's Republic of Korea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZI-6NARaLusC&pg=PA294|date=13 July 2012|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6151-0|page=294}}</ref> and it applied to join the IOC in June 1956.<ref name="GrassoMallon2015">{{cite book|last1=Grasso|first1=John|last2=Mallon|first2=Bill|last3=Heijmans|first3=Jeroen|title=Historical Dictionary of the Olympic Movement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uCN1CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA316|edition=5th|year=2015|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|location=Lanham|isbn=978-1-4422-4860-1|pages=315-316|chapter=Korea, Democratic People's Republic of (North Korea) (PRK)}}</ref>
In the 1957 session of the IOC, the [[Olympic Committee of the USSR]] asked the IOC to provisionally recognize the North Korean NOC on the grounds that the [[Nationales Olympisches Komitee für Ostdeutschland|East German NOC]] had been admitted alongside the [[Olympic Committee of West Germany]].<ref name="Hill1996"/> Recognition was to be done under the condition that the two Korean NOCs would agree to send a unified team to [[1960 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rome]],<ref name="Hill1996"/><ref name="GrassoMallon2015"/> but the plans failed due to opposition by the South's [[Korean Olympic Committee]].<ref name="GrassoMallon2015"/> The matter of a unified team was debated over the following sessions, and lobbied by the [[Bulgarian Olympic Committee|Bulgarian]] and [[Romanian Olympic and Sports Committee|Romanian NOC]]s, and in 1962 the IOC finally conferred provisional recognition on the North Korean NOC.<ref name="Hill1996"/>
Talks about a unified team continued in 1963, but these talks failed after the NOCs could agree on nothing but the flag, which was to consist of the word "Korea" under the [[Olympic rings]].<ref name="LamChang2006">{{cite book|author1=S. F. Lam|author2=Julian W. Chang|title=The Quest for Gold: Fifty Years of Amateur Sports in Hong Kong, 1947-1997|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y45FBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA137|year=2006|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-962-209-766-7|pages=137}}</ref>
Between 1985 and 1988 the NOCs negotiated about co-hosting the [[1988 Summer Olympics]]. The negotiations failed, resulting in North Korea boycotting the Games held in Seoul of South Korea.<ref name="GrassoMallon2015"/>
==National body members== The following national bodies have membership in the Committee: * [[Korea D.P.R. Amateur Athletics Federation]]<ref name="gtp">{{Cite web | title = Korea Democratic People's Republic Olympic Committee | publisher = Greek Travel Pages | work = gtp.gr | date = | accessdate = 2016-08-05 | url = https://www.gtp.gr/TDirectoryDetails.asp?id=48875 | language = | quote = }}</ref> * [[Korea D.P.R. Amateur Boxing Federation]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea D.P.R. Amateur Swimming Federation]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea D.P.R. Amateur Wrestling Federation]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea D.P.R. Badminton Association]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea D.P.R. Football Federation]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea D.P.R. Gymnastics Federation]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea D.P.R. Hockey Federation]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea D.P.R. Judo Federation]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea D.P.R. Rowing Federation]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea D.P.R. Table Tennis Association]]<ref name="gtp"/> * [[Korea DPR Weightlifting Association]]<ref name="gtp"/>
==2020 unified Korea team and 2032 co-host bid with South Korea== On November 2, 2018, officials from both North and South Korea announced that their countries would participate at the 2020 Summer Olympics, held in Tokyo, Japan, as a unified team.<ref name=nov2>https://edition.cnn.com/2018/11/02/sport/north-south-korea-tokyo-2020-olympics-spt-intl/index.html</ref><ref name=denvernov2>https://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/national/north-south-korea-set-to-combine-for-tokyo-2020-co-host-2032-olympics</ref> The officials from both Koreas also announced that the letters they would send to the IOC regarding their bids for hosting the 2032 Summer Olympics would also consist of co-host bids so that the Olympic activities would take place in both nations if their bids were accepted as well.<ref name=nov2 /><ref name=denvernov2 /><ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-2032-koreas/olympics-north-south-korea-to-send-letter-to-ioc-on-joint-2032-bid-idUSKCN1N70PT</ref>
